    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w34168</id>
    <title>Clinician Behavior When Skin-Tone Affects Test Results</title>
    <updated>2025-08-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Marcella Alsan, Liran Einav, Amy Finkelstein &amp; Jonathan Zhang</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We compare care for Black versus white patients following pulse oximetry, a widely-used device for measuring blood oxygen levels which over-estimates oxygen saturation in darker-skinned patients. Black patients are therefore medically more appropriate for follow-up care than white patients with the same pulse oximetry reading. Yet, using data from the Veterans Health Administration on 3.5 million emergency department visits between 2014 and 2018, we find that Black patients systematically receive lower rates of follow-up care than white patients with the same reading. Our findings illustrate how bias in a medical screening device is propagated and amplified in downstream care.</content>
