    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w34166</id>
    <title>Practical Finance: An Approximate Solution to Lifecycle Portfolio Choice</title>
    <updated>2025-08-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>James J. Choi, Canyao Liu &amp; Pengcheng Liu</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;Research on normative household financial choices almost always gives quantitative guidance in one of two forms: a simple formula for an unrealistic setting, or numerical solutions for only a few parameter sets in a realistic setting. We propose a middle-ground approach we call practical finance: analytic approximations to optimal solutions as a function of relevant parameters in realistic settings that are easily computed in a spreadsheet. We provide such an approximation for lifecycle portfolio choice with labor income. Across 5,103 parameter sets, our approximation results in welfare that is on average only 0.06% lower than that of the optimal solution.</content>
